@delong I think a reframing of (what I understand to be) your question will shed some light: Why did the American political order not successfully push back against neoliberalism?

@delong Implicit in that (possibly misconstrued) question is that the function of the American political order is to improve the economic lot of Americans, which neoliberalism failed to do.

@delong But that misconstrues both the purpose of the American political order and the goals of a significant segment of the American electorate.

@delong One significant goal of the American Constitution is to prevent people from successfully gaining their freedom from the rich who oppress them, either through outright state supported force (pre-Reconstruction era amendments) or through economic means.

@delong Meanwhile, one significant, and Constitutionally-overempowered segment of the population, has been convinced to focus on "pie in the sky when you die" rather than real world concerns.

@delong To take the non economic example de jour, the death and pain inflicted on women in Republican American who can't get treatment for ectopic pregnancies isn't a moral problem for religious believers who have faith in a God who will adjust the ledgers in the next world.

@delong (Here's  a friend of Dennis Prager explaining that he doesn't lose sleep over the evils of the Holocaust because he has faith that God granted Eichmann and Anne Frank different posthumous rewards. )https://t.co/iSvKYChb9C

@delong I'm not sure the American political order can successfully push back against the alliance of religious fanaticism and oligarchs, to which the ideology of neoliberalism provides useful talking points and intellectual cover.
